06943nam a22007815i 9781771123273DE-B159720240306010644.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20192018xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97817711232737 a10.51644/97817711232732doi  a(DE-B1597)667633  a(OCoLC)1085233159  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aPN1009.5.G48bC55 2018 7aLIT0090002bisacsh04a809/.8928200aChildren's Literature and Imaginative Geography /ced. by Aïda Hudson. 1aWaterloo, Ontario : bWilfrid Laurier University Press, c[2019] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (368 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction -- tGeographical Imaginaries -- tPullman and Imperialism -- tNineteenth-Century British Children’s Literature and the North -- tEnvisioning Ireland: Landscape and Longing in Children’s Literature -- tFrom Vanity to World’s Fair: The Landscape of John Bunyan’s Allegory in Frances Hodgson Burnett’s Two Little Pilgrims’ Progress -- tOld World, New World, Other World: Overcoming Prosaic Landscape with The Golden Pine Cone -- tHealing Relationships with the Natural Environment by Reclaiming Indigenous Space in Aaron Paquette’s Lightfinder -- tInterlude -- tHistory, Hills, and Lowlands: In Conversation with Janet Lunn -- tGardens and Green Places -- tHow Does Your Garden Grow? The Eco-Imaginative Space of the Garden in Contemporary Children’s Picture Books -- tInto the (Not So) Wild: Nature Without and Within in Kenneth Grahame’s The Wind in the Willows -- tInterlude -- tEarth, Sea, and Sky Writing in Becca at Sea -- tFantasy Worlds and Re-Enchantment -- tThe Imaginary North in Eileen Kernaghan’s The Snow Queen -- tCamping Out on the Quest: The Landscape of Boredom in Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows -- tSky Sailing: Steampunk’s Re-enchantment of Flight -- tMythic Re-enchantment: The Imaginative Geography of Madeleine L’Engle’s Time Quintet -- tSpace and Gender -- tFemale Places in Earthsea -- tDancing and Hinting at Worlds in Theatre for Young Audiences -- tPostlude -- tFollowing the Path of the Unconscious in the Owen Skye Books, and Others -- tWorks Cited -- tAbout the Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhere do children travel when they read a story? In this collection, scholars and authors explore the imaginative geography of a wide range of places, from those of Indigenous myth to the fantasy worlds of Middle-earth, Earthsea, or Pacificus, from the semi-fantastic Wild Wood to real-world places like Canada’s North, Chicago’s World Fair, or the modern urban garden. What happens to young protagonists who explore new worlds, whether fantastic or realistic? What happens when Old World and New World myths collide? How do Indigenous myth and sense of place figure in books for the young? How do environmental or post-colonial concerns, history, memory, or even the unconscious affect an author's creation of place? How are steampunk and science fiction mythically re-enchanting for children? Imaginative geography means imaged earth writing: it creates what readers see when they enter the world of fiction. Exploring diverse genres for children, including picture books, fantasy, steampunk, and realistic novels as well as plays from Canada, the United States, the United Kingdom, and Ireland from the early nineteenth century to the present, Children’s Literature and Imaginative Geography provides new geographical perspectives on children’s literature.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChildren's literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aGeography in literature. 0aImaginary places in literature. 4aGeography. 4aLiterary Criticism: Children’s Literature. 4aSocial Science